properties.headline: Blizzard Warning issued January 17 at 8:34PM CST until January 18 at 6:00PM CST by NWS Twin Cities/Chanhassen MN
properties.description:
...WINTER STORM WARNING TONIGHT FOLLOWED BY A BLIZZARD WARNING
SATURDAY FOR WESTERN INTO SOUTH CENTRAL MINNESOTA...

...WINTER STORM WARNING THROUGH SATURDAY FOR CENTRAL AND EASTERN
MINNESOTA INTO WEST CENTRAL WISCONSIN...

.Snow has tapered off across central and southern Minnesota this
evening and has transitioned to freezing drizzle along and south
of the I-94 corridor. This freezing drizzle transition will
continue into western Wisconsin tonight. Freezing drizzle will
last 3 to 5 hours at any one location before transitioning back to
snow for the rest of the storm. Additional snow accumulations of
1 to 3 inches through Saturday morning are expected, which will
bring storm total snowfall up to 4 to 7 inches across the area.

Blowing snow, with significant reductions in visibility will
occur early Saturday morning over western Minnesota as winds
increase from the northwest. The worst conditions will occur in
west central, and into south central Minnesota through the day
Saturday. Surface visibility will be near zero at times,
especially in open country. In addition, falling temperatures will
lead to icy roads and very cold temperatures.

* WHAT...For the Winter Storm Warning, mix of freezing drizzle and
snow. Additional snow accumulations of up to two inches and ice
accumulations of a light glaze. Winds gusting as high as 40 mph.
For the Blizzard Warning, widespread blowing snow and near zero
visibility will occur with blizzard conditions as northwest
winds gust as high as 50 mph.

* WHERE...Portions of central, south central, southwest and west
central Minnesota.

* WHEN...For the Winter Storm Warning, until 6 AM CST Saturday.
For the Blizzard Warning, from 6 AM to 6 PM CST Saturday.

* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. Areas of blowing
snow could significantly reduce visibility. Gusty winds could
bring down tree branches. The cold wind chills as low as 30
below zero could cause frostbite on exposed skin in as little
as 30 minutes.
properties.instruction:
If you must travel, keep an extra flashlight, food, and water in
your vehicle in case of an emergency.

Travel should be restricted to emergencies only. If you must
travel, have a winter survival kit with you. If you get stranded,
stay with your vehicle.

The latest road conditions for the state you are calling from can
be obtained by calling 5 1 1.

NWSheadline: WINTER STORM WARNING REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 AM CST SATURDAY... ...BLIZZARD WARNING REMAINS IN EFFECT FROM 6 AM TO 6 PM CST SATURDAY
